    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "you need to supply `min_periods`, which defaults to the window size.\n\nNote that using a numpy function directly with `.apply` is much slower (_some_ are mapped directly to the pandas impl, e.g. `np.mean`); I suppose `np.nan*` should be though they only exist in later versions of pandas.\n\n```\nIn [1]: df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 5, np.nan, np.nan]})\n\nIn [2]: df.rolling(3).apply(np.nanmean)\nOut[2]: \n    A\n0 NaN\n1 NaN\n2 NaN\n3 NaN\n4 NaN\n5 NaN\n\nIn [3]: df.rolling(3).mean()\nOut[3]: \n    A\n0 NaN\n1 NaN\n2 NaN\n3 NaN\n4 NaN\n5 NaN\n\nIn [4]: df.rolling(3, min_periods=1).apply(np.nanmean)\nOut[4]: \n     A\n0  NaN\n1  NaN\n2  NaN\n3  5.0\n4  5.0\n5  5.0\n\nIn [5]: df.rolling(3, min_periods=1).mean()\nOut[5]: \n     A\n0  NaN\n1  NaN\n2  NaN\n3  5.0\n4  5.0\n5  5.0\n```\n"
